---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
import SectionDivider from '../components/SectionDivider.astro';
import SourceLink from '../components/SourceLink.astro';
import SourceList from '../components/SourceList.astro';
import { withBase } from '../site';

const sources = [
  {
    title: 'Blakebrook Quarry endorsed as preferred landfill investigation site',
    publisher: 'Lismore App',
    date: '2025',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Lismore City Council — waste and resource recovery statements',
    publisher: 'Lismore City Council',
    url: 'https://www.lismore.nsw.gov.au/',
  },
  {
    title: 'Regional landfill site selection coverage',
    publisher: 'The Echo (Byron Shire)',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Northern Rivers waste shipped to Ipswich after 2022 flood',
    publisher: 'Waste Management Review',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Blakebrook basalt quarry operations',
    publisher: 'Quarry Magazine',
    note: 'URL to verify before publish.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What is actually being proposed"
  description="A plain-language, source-linked account of the proposed Blakebrook Quarry regional landfill: site, function, scale, the driver behind it, the timeline, and what the council says about safety."
  progress
  article
>
  <PageHeader eyebrow="The proposal" title="What is actually being proposed">
    A fair description, without critique. If you only read one page to
    understand the facts of the proposal, read this one.
  </PageHeader>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 pb-8">
    <div class="prose-body mt-10">
      <SectionDivider>1 — The site</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        The proposal concerns <strong>Blakebrook Quarry</strong>, near Nimbin,
        within the Lismore local government area. The site is currently an
        operating basalt quarry. In September 2025, Lismore councillors
        endorsed it as the <strong>preferred site to investigate</strong>,
        following assessment of more than thirty candidate locations.<SourceLink
          n={1}
        /><SourceLink n={2} />
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>2 — The function</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        The facility would be a disposal site for <strong
          >residual waste</strong
        > — waste that cannot be recycled or composted — and asbestos. It is
        <strong>not</strong> proposed as a public tip and would not replace the
        existing Lismore Recycling and Recovery Centre on Wyrallah Road, where
        residents drop off and sort waste.
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>3 — The scale</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        The facility is described at approximately <strong
          >60,000 tonnes per year</strong
        >, designed for a <strong>50-year operating life</strong>. Depending on
        assumptions about volume growth, that implies a total deposit on the
        order of <strong>1.8 to 3 million tonnes</strong> over its life. It
        would serve Lismore plus up to four neighbouring councils under a
        regional partnership.<SourceLink n={1} />
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>4 — The driver</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        The existing Cell 2B at the Wyrallah Road site has an estimated
        <strong>7&ndash;10 years</strong> of remaining capacity. The Wyrallah
        Road site was damaged in the <strong>February 2022 flood</strong>, and
        between 2022 and late 2025 the region&rsquo;s waste was transported to
        Ipswich, Queensland.<SourceLink n={4} /> Council frames the search for a
        long-term site as a responsible, generational decision rather than a
        crisis response.
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>5 — The timeline</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        On the current pathway, a concept design and business case would go to
        councillors in <strong>2027</strong>. If approved, the project would
        proceed to a full Environmental Impact Statement and NSW Government
        assessment. The total approval pathway is in the order of
        <strong>ten years</strong> from initiation — meaning waste would not be
        deposited at the site for many years even if every step were approved.
      </p>

      <SectionDivider>6 — What the council says about safety</SectionDivider>
      <p>
        The council&rsquo;s public position, articulated by the mayor, rests on
        three points: that <strong>NSW landfill regulation</strong> is the
        strictest in the country; that modern landfill engineering is
        sophisticated and &ldquo;not as simple as digging a hole and burying
        waste&rdquo;; and that a structured site-selection process — assessing
        many candidate sites against criteria — is the responsible way to make
        the decision.<SourceLink n={2} />
      </p>
      <p>
        We take each of these claims seriously and examine them on the{' '}
        <a href={withBase('/critique')}>critique page</a>. Several are accurate. The
        question this site asks is not whether the council is acting in bad
        faith — we assume it is not — but whether the public case has answered
        the standard siting questions a 50-year facility must clear.
      </p>
    </div>

    <SourceList sources={sources} />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
